There are several difficul- ties in this passage, and probably the read· . ing may be partly corrupt. ‘Apud te’ and ‘oul et’ are especially hard to explain. Diiring supposes a strong antithesis be· tween ‘ipse apud te precibus meis faveas ’ and ‘cui et indulgentiam tuam dabis,’ the former being a request for Trajan’s good opinion of Rosianus, the latter for some positive promoti0n‚ the ‘et' having a heightening force. But ‘ipse apud te' is a very awkward expression or ‘ in your own mind' and the ‘ preces’ are certainly not for Trajan’s good opinion, but for his ‘indulgentia¹; ‘pro dignitate’ again does not mean ‘as his worth deserves,’ but ‘ in a manner commensurate with his station.’ Precibus meis faveas, and indulgentiam tuam dare, must be taken as synonymous expressions, the latter serving somewhat clearly to define the former.
